"{\"type\": \"event\", \"name\": \"The Election of Andrew Jackson in 1828\", \"description\": \"Andrew Jackson's 1828 election epitomized the rise of the common man and reshaped American politics.\", \"introduction\": \"The election of Andrew Jackson in 1828 marked a significant shift in American politics, heralding the era of the 'common man' and the beginning of modern American democracy. It was characterized by the triumph of populism and a departure from the elitist political order. The lead-up included the contentious election of 1824, where Jackson won a plurality but lost in the House of Representatives, fueling a bitter rivalry and a campaign for revenge.\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1828-01-01\", \"end\": \"1828-12-31\"}, \"sections\": [{\"name\": \"The Corrupt Bargain of 1824\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1824-12-01\", \"end\": \"1824-12-31\"}, \"summary\": \"The 1824 election ended with no candidate receiving a majority in the Electoral College. The House of Representatives chose John Quincy Adams as President over Jackson, who had the most electoral votes, leading to allegations of a 'corrupt bargain' between Adams and Speaker of the House Henry Clay.\"}, {\"name\": \"Rise of Jacksonian Democracy\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1825-01-01\", \"end\": \"1828-01-01\"}, \"summary\": \"Between the 1824 and 1828 elections, Andrew Jackson's supporters built a political movement around his image as a war hero and man of the people, contrasting with Adams's elite image. This movement eventually became the Democratic Party, emphasizing states' rights and frontier values.\"}, {\"name\": \"The 1828 Campaign\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1828-01-01\", \"end\": \"1828-11-01\"}, \"summary\": \"The 1828 campaign was one of the first to see organized rallies, slogans, and smears, with Jackson portrayed as a man of the people and Adams as out-of-touch. Both sides engaged in bitter and personal attacks, marking a shift toward more populist campaigning methods.\"}, {\"name\": \"Voting Rights Expansion\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1820-01-01\", \"end\": \"1828-01-01\"}, \"summary\": \"During the 1820s, many states expanded the franchise by eliminating property requirements for voting. This change allowed a greater segment of the white male population to vote, which played into Jackson's base of support and influenced the outcome of the 1828 election.\"}, {\"name\": \"Election Day\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1828-11-04\", \"end\": \"1828-11-04\"}, \"summary\": \"On November 4, 1828, Jackson won a landslide victory over Adams, capturing the popular vote and a vast majority of the electoral votes. His victory was attributed to his appeal to ordinary voters and the expanded electorate.\"}, {\"name\": \"The Inauguration\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1829-03-04\", \"end\": \"1829-03-04\"}, \"summary\": \"Andrew Jackson's inauguration on March 4, 1829, was a public spectacle. Thousands of supporters flocked to Washington, D.C., to celebrate. The event was symbolic of the political power shifting towards the common man.\"}], \"conclusion\": \"The election of Andrew Jackson in 1828 was a watershed moment in American politics. It represented a profound shift towards populist democracy, the empowerment of the average citizen, and the foundation of the modern two-party system, which would shape the future of American politics.\", \"people\": [{\"name\": \"Andrew Jackson\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1767-03-15\", \"end\": \"1845-06-08\"}, \"description\": \"7th President of the United States, a war hero, and the symbol of the 'common man's' rise to political power.\"}, {\"name\": \"John Quincy Adams\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1767-07-11\", \"end\": \"1848-02-23\"}, \"description\": \"6th President of the United States and the incumbent defeated by Jackson in the 1828 election.\"}, {\"name\": \"Henry Clay\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1777-04-12\", \"end\": \"1852-06-29\"}, \"description\": \"Speaker of the House who was accused of orchestrating the 'corrupt bargain' that led to Adams's presidency.\"}, {\"name\": \"Martin Van Buren\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1782-12-05\", \"end\": \"1862-07-24\"}, \"description\": \"Key organizer of Jackson's 1828 campaign and a founder of the Democratic Party.\"}], \"places\": [{\"name\": \"Washington, D.C.\", \"description\": \"The capital of the United States and the location of Jackson's iconic inauguration.\"}, {\"name\": \"Tennessee\", \"description\": \"Andrew Jackson's home state and a stronghold of his political support.\"}, {\"name\": \"White House\", \"description\": \"The residence of the President, symbolizing the office that Jackson captured from John Quincy Adams.\"}, {\"name\": \"United States\", \"description\": \"The nation that experienced a shift in its political and electoral landscape with Jackson's election.\"}], \"next\": [{\"name\": \"The Spoils System and Civil Service Reform\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1829-01-01\", \"end\": \"1883-01-16\"}, \"description\": \"The practice of patronage under Jackson's presidency and subsequent efforts for reform.\", \"connection\": \"Effect\"}, {\"name\": \"The Nullification Crisis\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1832-11-24\", \"end\": \"1833-03-15\"}, \"description\": \"A sectional crisis during Jackson's presidency involving confrontation between South Carolina and the federal government.\", \"connection\": \"Effect\"}, {\"name\": \"The Indian Removal Act and the Trail of Tears\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1830-05-28\", \"end\": \"1839-12-31\"}, \"description\": \"Jackson's policies leading to the forced relocation of Native American tribes.\", \"connection\": \"Effect\"}, {\"name\": \"The Bank War\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1832-01-01\", \"end\": \"1836-01-01\"}, \"description\": \"Andrew Jackson's campaign against the Second Bank of the United States.\", \"connection\": \"Effect\"}, {\"name\": \"Expansion of the Franchise in the Early 19th Century\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1800-01-01\", \"end\": \"1828-01-01\"}, \"description\": \"The broader movement towards democratic reforms that set the stage for Jackson's election.\", \"connection\": \"Cause\"}, {\"name\": \"The Corrupt Bargain: A Closer Look\", \"dates\": {\"start\": \"1824-12-01\", \"end\": \"1825-01-01\"}, \"description\": \"An in-depth examination of the events and allegations surrounding the 1824 presidential election.\", \"connection\": \"Deep dive\"}]}"